docs.abstract: Known as Daddy-O, he created roadside, streetside and top-of-the-roof attractions in Texas and elsewhere.
docs.snippet: Known as Daddy-O, he created roadside, streetside and top-of-the-roof attractions in Texas and elsewhere.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bob Wade, a Texas artist whose 40-foot-long iguana sculpture once perched atop the Lone Star Cafe in Manhattan and whose 63-foot-high saxophone lured patrons to a blues nightclub in Houston, died on Dec. 24 at his home in Austin. He was 76.

headline.main: Bob Wade, Sculptor of the Outlandishly Large, Dies at 76
headline.print_headline: Bob Wade, Creator of Whimsical Art (the Bigger the Better), Dies at 76

docs.abstract: Scientists knew octopuses and squid didn’t have any depth perception, but they had a hunch their cuttlefish cousins might.
docs.snippet: Scientists knew octopuses and squid didn’t have any depth perception, but they had a hunch their cuttlefish cousins might.
docs.lead_paragraph: The cuttlefish hovers in the aquarium, its fins rippling and large, limpid eyes glistening. When a scientist drops a shrimp in, this cousin of the squid and octopus pauses, aims and shoots its tentacles around the prize.

headline.main: Yes, This Cuttlefish Is Wearing 3-D Glasses
headline.print_headline: Seeing is Believing: Yes, This Cuttlefish Is Wearing 3-D Glasses

docs.abstract: Only 14 were selected to be on the Disney Parks Moms Panel (three are dads), and they will spend the next year helping interested parkgoers plan their Disney vacations.
docs.snippet: Only 14 were selected to be on the Disney Parks Moms Panel (three are dads), and they will spend the next year helping interested parkgoers plan their Disney vacations.
docs.lead_paragraph: At 7:30 in the morning on a recent Saturday, 14 people gathered on the 10th floor of Disney’s Riviera Resort in Orlando, Fla., at the Topolino’s Terrace restaurant. The resort would open in two days, and this group had been among the first to experience it — a treat for many, but especially for this collection of self-described Disney superfans.

headline.main: Would You Work for Nothing at Disney? 10,000 Superfans Applied
headline.print_headline: Work for Disney Without Pay? 10,000 Applied

docs.abstract: Britain and the European Union now face the all-but-impossible task of drawing up a comprehensive trade deal in a year’s time.
docs.snippet: Britain and the European Union now face the all-but-impossible task of drawing up a comprehensive trade deal in a year’s time.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Like ex-spouses who have just signed divorce papers but not yet begun the ugly business of dividing their possessions, Britain and the European Union are tiptoeing around each other as the year begins, desperate to keep their dealings civil even as they gird for the unpleasantness to come.

headline.main: And You Thought Brexit Was Tough …
headline.print_headline: Britain and E.U. Smile, But Expect Gritted Teeth

docs.abstract: Hazard reduction is more complex than some would have you believe.
docs.snippet: Hazard reduction is more complex than some would have you believe.
docs.lead_paragraph: CANBERRA, Australia — Every state in Australia has been touched by fire since the season started in September. The fires have burned over 12 million acres, an area larger than Maryland. Four hundred and eighty million animals are estimated to be killed or badly injured. Thousands of people have been evacuated. At least 24 have died.

docs.abstract: The president and his allies are trying to make Democratic plans to reform law enforcement a potent campaign issue.
docs.snippet: The president and his allies are trying to make Democratic plans to reform law enforcement a potent campaign issue.
docs.lead_paragraph: Unexpectedly, the 2020 presidential campaign is drilling down on petty crime and homelessness. Donald Trump and his Republican allies are reviving law-and-order themes similar to those used effectively by Richard Nixon and Spiro Agnew in the late 1960s and early 1970s to demonize racial minorities.

headline.main: Trump Wants Law and Order Front and Center

docs.abstract: The country is moving beyond nuclear power. But at what cost?
docs.snippet: The country is moving beyond nuclear power. But at what cost?
docs.lead_paragraph: HAMBURG, Germany — Are the Germans irrational? Steven Pinker seems to think so. Professor Pinker, a Harvard psychologist, told the German newsmagazine Der Spiegel recently that if mankind wanted to stop climate change without stopping economic growth too, the world needed more nuclear energy, not less. Germany’s decision to step out of nuclear, he agreed, was “paranoid.”

headline.main: The Tragedy of Germany’s Energy Experiment
